In the worldwide search for a response to the COVID-19 pandemic, news about “alternative remedies against COVID” have been disseminated (
 ANSES, 2020; 
 Nordling, 2020). As of July 2020, the evidence-base for such treatments is often limited if not non-existent. However, often strong, unsubstantiated claims are made about the pros and cons of herbal medicines, which will also result both in false hopes or strong fears of those at risk or ill with COVID-19 (
 Brennen et al., 2020; 
 Guastalegname and Vallone, 2020; 
 Thorp, 2020).
